At this rate, you would end up struggling to memorize kanji because in Japanese, many kanji have multiple readings.

Of course, there are no patterns, so you have to drill all of its meanings and pronunciations into your head with great effort.
If you're having difficulty even remembering hiragana and katakana, then I hate to say this, but I recommend you should learn another language.

>>176129764
The TRAP vowel is like the "a" in "maths", or like the "a" here in passage (ˈpæsJd͡ʒ) in RP. It isn't based on any genuine south-eastern accent, but was rather created at some point in the early 20th century when radio became common throughout England. The BBC created it a standardised pronunciation to be used on all of their news broadcasts. As another poster pointed out, it was made to give the impression of an educated wealthy speaker, who when listened to would make you feel like you were being told the truth, simply put. It does definitely make you sound posh, especially if you travel anywhere outside of tourist-y parts of london. It's a double-edged sword as in some circles or places it can make people feel more at ease with you if you sound posh, like if you are mixing with lots of rich people, businessmen, bankers, city workers, the like. However, in most places, it will just make you stand out and you will more than likely be judged for it.

>>176143951
They're all different. Besides, <ʃ> is an ambiguous symbol because it can stand for both flat and domed postalveolars.
In isolation, Ukrainian only has the former, while most dialects of English may have either depending on the speaker. In both languages the sounds are affected by vowel context, meaning that they will always be more palatalized before vowels like [i].
The Russian щ sound is a strongly domed postalveolar regardless of its position, and its tongue shape is essentially the same as in the words "she" or "нaшi".

It's not in the circled area though.
> And have then "ship" and "sheep" got the same consonant?
As I said, there is no single "palatalized" version of consonants in English. They are all affected by adjacent vowels to differing degrees, and if the vowel is high and front enough to change the acoustics (namely by raising F2), then we can call the resulting sound palatalized.
> Shalln't we pronounce just not-palatalized [ш]-like sound always
You can definitely do it, but I thought you were going for a perfect accent? I think you should just do shadowing. It's helpful to know the theory but you still need to internalize it by copying native speakers.

posts.com:
I firmly believe that societies which regularly use logogram/pictogram based scripts tend to become linguistically stunted.
Examination of japanese and chinese literature, as well as their everday conversations confirms this thesis. They may have a large vocabulary akin to other languages, but compared to others they use an extremely small number of these words on a day to day basis, completely repeating the same phrases and words to the point of bad taste. It is impossible to find "purple prose" literature written in such languages (that is, by the writers whose native tongue is that which employs a logogram script). Another issue is that cultures/languages which evolve with logograms also evolve an unnaturally large number of homonyms, to the point that if they wanted to switch to an alphabet based script they would most likely have to either invent an enormous amount of new words or take in a lot of loan words from other languages.

My God, pictograms. Not even once. Am I glad for the roman/greek legacy.

I wouldn't disregard the importance of going to the moon, even if someone gets a man on Mars first.
Any real Mars project (anything other than a "we put a man on Mars!" PR gimmick) is going to require a lunar base where sub-critical amounts of nuclear fuel brought up from Earth will be converted to usable fuel cells for the Mars ships which will ferry whatever is needed between Mars and the Moon. Other approaches have very little potential to sustain a long-term operation at least somewhat economically.
That being said, I don't think China has what it takes to accomplish this in foreseeable future. Maybe the USA would be able to do it through NASA/SpaceX collaboration, but I don't think they have the will to invest the absurdly high amount of resources needed into it. After all, we really don't know if there's anything on Mars to justify mining it. Talks of colonization and terraformation are pure sci-fi as long as we can't even terraform the Sahara here on Earth.
In my opinion, a much more realistic target for space exploitation are the asteroids between Mars and Jupiter, as there is a good chance that a lot of them are full of scarce metals. Mining them would also require a lunar "space base camp" though, so once again, the Moon is the obligatory first step.
